0–1282","1220–1250":"1220–1250","1292–1367":"1292–1367","1340–1402":"1340–1402","1162–Male":"1162–Overleden","1170–Female":"1170–Overleden","1402":"1402","1367":"1367","1210":"1210","1220":"1220","1340":"1340","1162":"1162","1250":"1250","1282":"1282","1292":"1292","1170":"1170","West Hall, Cheshire, England":"Westhall, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Coton Hall, Alveley Parish, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1210–1282":"1210–1282","1220–1250":"1220–1250","1292–1367":"1292–1367","1340–1402":"1340–1402","1162–Male":"1162–Deceased","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1402":"1402","1367":"1367","1210":"1210","1220":"1220","1340":"1340","1162":"1162","1250":"1250","1282":"1282","1292":"1292","1170":"1170","West Hall, Cheshire, England":"Westhall, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Coton Hall, Alveley Parish, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leigh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places (in at least sixteen counties, but especially Leigh in Lancashire) named either with the nominative case of Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’ (see   Lee  ) or with <i>lēage</i>, a late dative form of this word (see   Lye  ).","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 李, based on its Cantonese pronunciation. See   Li   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Leah","meanings":["English: variant of   Leigh  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 李 and 利, see   Li   1 and 3."]},{"name":"Lee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sang, Jae, Jong, Jung, Sung, Yong, Kyung, Seung, Dong, Kwang, Myung.","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a meadow or a patch of arable land, Middle English <i>lee</i>, <i>lea</i>, from Old English <i>lēa</i>, dative case (used after a preposition) of <i>lēah</i>, which originally meant ‘wood or glade’.","English: habitational name from any of the many places in England named with Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade’, including Lee in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Kent, and Shropshire, and Lea in Cheshire, Derbyshire, Herefordshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, and Wiltshire."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Leigh was born in 1210, in Westhall, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Gilbert Legh, was 48 and her mother, Margery Hatton, was 40. She had at least 1 son with William LEE. She died in 1282, in Coton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1210–1282":"1210–1282","1220–1250":"1220–1250","1292–1367":"1292–1367","1340–1402":"1340–1402","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1402":"1402","1367":"1367","1210":"1210","1220":"1220","1340":"1340","1162":"1162","1250":"1250","1282":"1282","1292":"1292","1170":"1170","West Hall, Cheshire, England":"Westhall, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Coton Hall, Alveley Parish, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1210–1282":"1210–1282",